     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">Technical Meetings: Two technical meeting were held during the reporting cycle by the NDA as part of the process of developing Ghana&#x2019;s GCF Country Programme. The meetings was used to provide technical input on the draft Country Programme, which has subsequently been submitted to the GCF for review.

Translation and dissemination of no-objection procedures: The activity focused on disseminating the translated no-objection procedures at the sub-national level. The dissemination was done in 4 major local Ghanaian languages in 5 administrative regions of Ghana, namely Greater Accra, Ashanti, Northern and Volta regions. A total of 1,000 copies of the translated no-objection was distributed during the exercise. The number of people engaged during the exercise was 540 people of which approximately 40% were female and 60% male. With this, the dissemination at the sub-national level can be said to be completed.

Developing EWP: An Entity Work Programme (EWP) was developed for Ecobank Ghana Limited, the only GCF Direct Access Entity in Ghana.

The EWP though not mandatory, would provide Ecobank Ghana Limited with a clear programme of action and would give the needed guidance internally for Ecobank on the priority areas they would want to focus on, in line with Ghana GCF Country Programme and overall NDCs.

Private sector investment forum: A two-day Private Sector Climate Change Investment Forum to build on already existing efforts in the promotion of private sector participation in identified climate actions was organized by the Private Enterprise Federation in partnership with the Ministry of Finance (MOF) acting as the National Designated Authority of the Green Climate Fund (GCF), Ministry of Environment, Science, Technology and Innovation (MESTI) and the United Nations Development Programme under the GCF Readiness Programme to Ghana. 

The Forum on the theme Empowering the Private Sector as a Key Partner in Achieving Ghanas NDCs in the Era of Covid-19 and Beyond sought to provide a platform to engage private sector players, funding agencies and public sector institutions on opportunities and risks in climate change investment space in Ghana along the prioritized sectors under the Ghana Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs).

Private sector concept note: The private sector, led by the Private Enterprises Federation led the development of a concept note on hybrid solar PV and waste-to-energy (W2E) technologies to address environmental or waste challenges as well as augment the energy needs of organisations. 

Despite the abundant availability of feedstock (biowaste) for bioenergy generations in Ghana, the country is yet to develop a significant programme that will promote the dissemination of waste to energy plants on a larger scale. This concept note that has been submitted to the Ghana NDA and the GCF seeks to generate relevant private sector and GCF funding to facilitate investments in the waste to energy sector of Ghana, in line with Ghana&#x2019;s NDCs.</narrative>
      </comment>
